Conscious of the mission incumbent upon them of preserving the cultural heritage of mankind and of promoting the development of science, arts and letters;

Mindful that this development depends in a large measure upon intellec- tual co-operation;

Having noted the importance of the efforts made to this end by the

International Intellectual Co-operation Organisation and its various consti- tuent bodies;

Believing that the cause of peace would be served by the promotion of cul- tural relations between peoples through the action of an intellectual organi- sation possessing the threefold character of universality, permanence and independence;

Recognising that the Intellectual Go-operation Organisation constitutes for the ligh Contracting Parties a free association, devoid of any political character and with no purpose except the furtherance of intellectual co- operation;

